Idea

Pointer i keeps track of the last unique element.

Pointer j scans the array.

When nums[j] is different from nums[i], move i forward and copy the value.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)

C++ Code ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
class Solution {
public:
    int removeDuplicates(vector<int>& nums) {
        int i = 0;

        for(int j = 1; j < nums.size(); j++){
            if(nums[j] != nums[i]){
                i++;
                nums[i] = nums[j];
            }
        }

        return i + 1;
    }
};



Example

Input
[0,0,1,1,1,2,2,3,3,4]

Process keeps only unique values in front:

[0,1,2,3,4,_,_,_,_,_]

Return
k = 5

So the first 5 elements are the unique sorted numbers.
